{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b5869f8-b2da-4d6f-aed8-8625c9446898","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe issue is clear: `dotnet build` pays MSBuild **process startup + project re-evaluation** cost on every invocation, while Visual Studio keeps a long-lived MSBuild server in memory.\n\n## Recommendations\n\nHere are the fixes, ordered by impact:\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop (biggest win)\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\nKeeps the process alive and only rebuilds on file changes — no repeated startup cost.\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server (.NET 8+)\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nThis keeps a long-lived MSBuild server process between CLI invocations, mimicking VS behavior.\n\n### 3. Ensure MSBuild node reuse is enabled\n```bash\n# Verify this is NOT set in your environment:\n#   MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1\n# Then build with node reuse explicitly:\ndotnet build -nodeReuse:true\n```\nKeeps MSBuild worker nodes warm between builds so subsequent invocations skip process spin-up.\n\n### 4. Add `UseSharedCompilation` to the project\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <UseSharedCompilation>true</UseSharedCompilation>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\nKeeps the Roslyn compiler server (VBCSCompiler) alive between builds. Usually on by default, but worth verifying.\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** For fast edit-build-test cycles, use `dotnet watch build`. For one-off CLI builds, set `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` in your shell profile to get VS-like warm-server performance.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"400bf9bb-e33f-47da-a91a-b9e1164866c0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer is reporting that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio builds are nearly instant. They've already verified that analyzers aren't the issue and that incremental build targets are working correctly.\n\nThe root cause they identified is: \"MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\"\n\nThis is a well-known issue in the .NET ecosystem. Visual Studio keeps an MSBuild server process running (long-lived), so it doesn't pay the startup cost on each build. The CLI (`dotnet build`) by default starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n \nThere are a few ways to address this. The main fix is enabling MSBuild server mode, either through the `-nodeReuse:true` flag or the `MSBUILDENABLESERVERMODE=1` environment variable—this keeps MSBuild nodes alive between builds and eliminates that startup overhead. For development workflows, `dotnet watch` is another option since it maintains a running process and only rebuilds when files change. There's also the `-graph` flag for static graph evaluation, which can improve performance in certain scenarios. The most impactful optimization is enabling the MSBuild Server in .NET 8, which maintains a long-lived process to avoid startup overhead—I can enable this through an environment variable or by configuring the project to use shared compilation. Let me clarify the distinction between the MSBuild server and the Roslyn compiler server, since they're separate features that both improve build performance. For practical optimization, `dotnet watch build` is the best approach since it eliminates CLI startup overhead on each rebuild, while enabling MSBuild node reuse with `-nr:true` and the build server via `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` provides additional warmth between invocations.","outputTokens":1585,"requestId":"5C28:70BC2:6190BA2:6A5827C:69F15601"},"id":"a74d710f-7214-4620-9bdc-f2375998a0a7","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:51:44.611Z","parentId":"da8819b5-f75b-45d8-ba62-6e70c1ff5c82"}
